{"id":"trail-ridge-road","generatedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z","designation":"All-American Road","parkCode":"romo","source":{"roadArticle":"Trail Ridge Road","revisionId":1301637710,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trail_Ridge_Road"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trail_Ridge_Road","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Trail Ridge Road\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trail_Ridge_Road","revisionId":1301637710,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"National Park Service","src":"nps","url":"https://www.nps.gov/romo","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"}],"endpoints":null,"itinerary":[],"history":{"paragraphs":["Trail Ridge had been used by Native Americans to cross the mountains between their home lands in the west and hunting areas on the east side. Arapahoe Indians called the trail located on the ridge as \"taienbaa\" (\"Where the Children Walked\") because it was so steep that children could not be carried, but had to walk. The Ute tribe crossing the mountains at Forest Canyon Pass marked their route with stone cairns. The present park Ute Trail follows partially that ancient route.","On the west side, about 1880, a wagon road was constructed along the Kawuneeche Valley from the town of Grand Lake to the mining camps of Lulu City and Gaskill. The camps were abandoned after a few years when short-lived mining boom ended and later the road was used only occasionally by hunters and tourists.","Fall River Road was the first road into the park's high country. It opened in 1921 and quickly proved inadequate for motor travel as a single-track road with steep grades (up to 16%), tight curves and a short annual season due to snowpack. Construction began in 1929 and was complete to Fall River Pass by July 1932, with a maximum grade of 7%. The road was complete through the Kawuneeche Valley to Grand Lake in 1938. The route followed what was known to local Arapaho Indians as the Dog Trail. Internal opposition to the construction of a road through the park's alpine tundra was overruled by National Park Service director Horace Albright, who wished to encourage park visitation. The road was designed to intrude as little as possible into the landscape, in accordance with Park Service design principles.","Hidden Valley (or Ski Estes Park) was a local ski area attraction from 1955 – 1991, off of Trail Ridge Road, now defunct."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"\"Trail Ridge Road: Rocky Mountain National Park\". Colorado Department of Transportation. 2021. Retrieved April 8, 2022.","url":"https://www.codot.gov/travel/colorado-byways/north-central/trail-ridge-rd"},{"n":2,"text":"\"Trail Ridge Road / Beaver Meadow Road\". America's Scenic Byways. Retrieved April 8, 2022.","url":"https://scenicbyways.info/byway/2102.html"},{"n":3,"text":"\"National Register Information System\". National Register of Historic Places. National Park Service. July 9, 2010. Retrieved September 29, 2013.","url":"https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP"},{"n":4,"text":"\"Forest Health\". National Park Service. Retrieved January 12, 2013. Road crews use tall and narrow trees as snow poles to mark road edges affected by deep snow. These snow poles help facilitate plowing operations throughout the year, especially when opening Trail Ridge Road.","url":"https://home.nps.gov/romo/learn/nature/forest_health_park_efforts.htm"},{"n":5,"text":"Quin, Richard (August 1993). Trail Ridge Road, Rocky Mountain National Park, HAER No. CO-31 (PDF). Historic American Engineering Record. Washington D.C.: National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior. Retrieved June 8, 2020.","url":"https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/master/pnp/habshaer/co/co0100/co0193/data/co0193data.pdf"},{"n":6,"text":"\"PRISM Climate Group, Oregon State University\". PRISM Climate Group, Oregon State University. Retrieved October 10, 2023. To find the table data on the PRISM website, start by clicking Coordinates (under Location); copy Latitude and Longitude figures from top of table; click Zoom","url":"http://prism.oregonstate.edu/explorer/"},{"n":7,"text":"\"Scenic Drives\". Rocky Mountain National Park. National Park Service. Archived from the original on December 30, 2006. Retrieved August 23, 2007.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20061230002415/http://www.nps.gov/archive/romo/visit/weather/scenicdrives.html"},{"n":8,"text":"\"History of Trail Ridge Road\". Rocky Mountain National Park. National Park Service. Retrieved August 29, 2011.","url":"https://home.nps.gov/romo/learn/historyculture/trail_ridge_road_history.htm"}],"routeLine":[[40.3872,-105.61266],[40.38718,-105.6118],[40.38714,-105.61088],[40.38689,-105.61009],[40.38663,-105.60935],[40.38635,-105.60861],[40.38612,-105.60771],[40.38591,-105.60695],[40.38556,-105.60625],[40.38512,-105.60569],[40.3845,-105.60559],[40.38387,-105.60592],[40.38327,-105.60597],[40.38247,-105.60513],[40.38188,-105.60497],[40.38125,-105.60495],[40.38075,-105.60438],[40.38063,-105.60358],[40.38098,-105.60277],[40.38148,-105.60207],[40.38173,-105.60134],[40.3814,-105.60063],[40.38083,-105.60019],[40.38008,-105.59964],[40.3796,-105.5992],[40.379,-105.59835],[40.3777,-105.59736],[40.37701,-105.59695],[40.3764,-105.59653],[40.37592,-105.59596],[40.37486,-105.594],[40.37449,-105.59333],[40.37404,-105.59276],[40.37339,-105.59214],[40.37286,-105.59162],[40.37232,-105.59086],[40.37196,-105.59013],